<subsection>
    <title>Evaluating limits Definition of Limits</title>

    <p> Let's make sure the definition makes sense. Here is a nice first problem to attempt.</p>

<example xml:id="ex-0001">
<title>Our First Limit</title>
<statement>
        <p>
          Consider the function <m>f(x) = \dfrac{x^3-2x^2+x-2}{x-2}</m>
          
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li><p>Using a calculator, evaluate the function at the indicated <m>x</m>-values and fill in the corresponding entries in the table.</p> 

              <me>
                \begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
            \hline
            x \amp 1 \amp 1.9 \amp 1.99 \amp 2 \amp 2.01 \amp 2.1 \amp 3 \\
            \hline
            f(x) \amp  \amp  \amp  \amp \text{Undefined} \amp  \amp  \amp  \\
            \hline
            \end{array}
              </me>
              
          
            </li>

            <li>Based on the intuitive limit definition guess the limit value <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2} \dfrac{x^3-2x^2+x-2}{x-2}</m></li>
            <li>View <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/jxcqa9k7jo" visual="">the graph of <m>f(x)</m> in Desmos</url>. Use words to explain to another student how the table relates to the graph and how the limit can 
            be determined from the graph.</li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <alert>Check Your Answers:</alert>
        </p>
          <ol marker="(a)">
            <li><p> </p> 

              <me>
                \begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
            \hline
            x \amp 1 \amp 1.9 \amp 1.99 \amp 2 \amp 2.01 \amp 2.1 \amp 3 \\
            \hline
            f(x) \amp  2 \amp 4.61 \amp 4.9601 \amp \text{Undefined} \amp 5.0401 \amp 5.41 \amp 10 \\
            \hline
            \end{array}
              </me>
              
          
            </li>

            <li><m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 2} \dfrac{x^3-2x^2+x-2}{x-2} = 5</m></li>
            <li>
                As <m>x</m> approaches <m>2</m> from either the left or the right, the output values <m>f(x)</m> get closer and closer to <m>5</m>. 
                Although <m>f(2)</m> is undefined (there is a hole in the graph), the limit still exists and equals <m>5</m>.
            </li>
          </ol>
          
          <p><alert>Step by Step Video Solution:</alert></p>
          <p>
              <video youtube="eYcCeFBrLqc" width="90%">
              </video>
          </p>

    </solution>
    </example>


    <p>
       Some limits are easy because we can plug in <m>x = a</m> to get the limiting value 
       <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to a} f(x) = f(a)</m>, in which case we say <m>f(x)</m> is <term>continuous</term> at <m>x = a</m>. 
       Graphically, as in the <xref ref="fig-limit-graph">above figure</xref>, this means the curve has no jump or hole at <m>(a, f(a))</m>.
    </p>
    

  <example xml:id="ex-limit-continuous">
    <title>A Nice Continuous Example</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 5} x^2 </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p><alert>Full Written Solution:</alert></p>
      <p>
        Since our function <m>f(x) = x^2</m> is continuous around <m>x = 5</m> (we can draw the parabola without lifting our pencil), 
        we can simply plug <m>x = 5</m> into <m>f(x)</m> to get the answer <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \to 5} x^2 = 25</m>.
      </p>
      <p><alert>More Rigorous Solution:</alert></p>
      <p>
        Algebraically, if <m>x</m> is close enough to <m>5</m>, say <m>x = 5 + h</m> for some small <m>h</m> (close to <m>0</m>), then 
        <me>
        x^2 = (5 + h)^2 = 5^2 + 2(5h) + h^2 = 25 + 10h + h^2
        </me>
        which is forced as close as we like to <m>L = 25</m> if <m>h</m> is small enough to 0 (either positive or negative).
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>


<p>
We have seen a few problems where a limit exists, but in fact, as the 2004 movie <em>Mean Girls</em> teaches us, sometimes
</p>

<figure>
  <image source="images/NoLimit.gif">
  </image>
  <caption>
    The limit does not exist GIF
  </caption>
</figure>

<p>
  One way this can occur is if <m>f(x)</m> does not approach a single limiting value as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m>. 
  In such cases, we declare that the <em>limit does not exist</em>, and the symbol <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x \to a} f(x)</m> has no meaning. 
  Now let's see such an example.
</p>


  <example xml:id="ex-limit-does-not-exist">
    <title>When a limit does not exist</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the sign function <m>\operatorname{sgn}(x)=\dfrac{x}{|x|}</m> for <m>x\ne 0</m>,
        undefined at <m>x=0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <figure>
      <caption>The graph of <m>\operatorname{sgn}(x)</m>.</caption>
      <image source="1-5-Sgn.png"/>
    </figure>
    <solution>
      <p>
        As <m>x\to 0^+</m>, <m>\operatorname{sgn}(x)=1</m>, while as <m>x\to 0^-</m>,
        <m>\operatorname{sgn}(x)=-1</m>. There is no single limiting value at <m>0</m>, so
        <m>\lim_{x\to 0} \operatorname{sgn}(x)</m> does not exist.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>



 </subsection>






  <example xml:id="ex-removable-hole">
    <title>Limit exists though the function is undefined at <m>a</m></title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 1} \dfrac{x^2-1}{x-1}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <figure>
      <caption>A removable discontinuity at <m>x=1</m>.</caption>
      <image source="1-5-Removable-2.png"/>
    </figure>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Factor and cancel: <m>\dfrac{x^2-1}{x-1}=\dfrac{(x-1)(x+1)}{x-1}=x+1</m> for
        <m>x\ne 1</m>. Since <m>x+1</m> is continuous,
        <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 1} \dfrac{x^2-1}{x-1} = \lim_{x\to 1}(x+1)=2</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <definition xml:id="def-one-sided">
    <title>One-sided limits</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The right-hand limit <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a^+} f(x)=L</m> means
        <m>f(x)</m> can be made arbitrarily close to <m>L</m> by taking <m>x&gt;a</m>
        sufficiently close to <m>a</m>. The left-hand limit
        <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a^-} f(x)=L</m> is defined similarly using <m>x&lt;a</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <discussion>
      <p>
        The (two-sided) limit <m>\lim_{x\to a} f(x)</m> exists and equals <m>L</m> if and only if
        both one-sided limits exist and are equal to <m>L</m>.
      </p>
    </discussion>
  </definition>

  <definition xml:id="def-infinite-limit">
    <title>Infinite limits and vertical asymptotes</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        We write <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a} f(x)=\infty</m> to indicate that the values
        of <m>f(x)</m> grow beyond any bound as <m>x</m> approaches <m>a</m> (from either side).
        Likewise, <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to a} f(x)=-\infty</m> indicates unbounded
        decrease. Such behavior signals a vertical asymptote at <m>x=a</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <figure xml:id="fig-absx-reciprocal">
    <caption><m>y=\dfrac{1}{|x|}</m> has an infinite limit at <m>x=0</m>.</caption>
    <image source="1-5-Asymp.png"/>
  </figure>

  <example xml:id="ex-one-sided-infinite">
    <title>One-sided infinite limits for <m>\dfrac{1}{x}</m></title>
    <figure>
      <caption><m>y=\dfrac{1}{x}</m> has opposite behavior on each side of <m>x=0</m>.</caption>
      <image source="1-5-Asymp-2.png"/>
    </figure>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 0^-}\dfrac{1}{x}=-\infty</m> and
        <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 0^+}\dfrac{1}{x}=\infty</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="ex-vertical-asymptotes-signs">
    <title>Determining vertical asymptotes and their signs</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Analyze <m>\displaystyle f(x)=\dfrac{2x-4}{x^2-4x+3}=\dfrac{2(x-2)}{(x-1)(x-3)}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Zeros occur where the numerator vanishes: <m>x=2</m>. The denominator vanishes at
        <m>x=1</m> and <m>x=3</m>, producing vertical asymptotes there (no common factors).
        Sign analysis shows:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 1^-} f(x)=-\infty</m>, <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 1^+} f(x)=\infty</m>.</li>
        <li><m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 3^-} f(x)=-\infty</m>, <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 3^+} f(x)=\infty</m>.</li>
      </ul>
    </solution>
    <figure>
      <caption>Graph of <m>f(x)=\dfrac{2(x-2)}{(x-1)(x-3)}</m> with vertical asymptotes.</caption>
      <image source="1-5-Asymp-3.png"/>
    </figure>
    <remark>
      <p>
        If <m>f(x)=\dfrac{2x-2}{x^2-4x+3}=\dfrac{2(x-1)}{(x-1)(x-3)}</m>, then the common factor cancels:
        there is a removable discontinuity (a hole) at <m>x=1</m>, not a vertical asymptote.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </example>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-graphical-limits">
    <title>Practice</title>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>From a graph of a function with a hole at <m>x=4</m> but approaching height <m>3</m>, determine <m>\lim_{x\to 4} f(x)</m> and whether <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>4</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>Recall that limits depend on nearby values, not on <m>f(4)</m>.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Decide whether <m>\lim_{x\to 0} \dfrac{|x|}{x}</m> exists. Justify using one-sided limits.</p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>Find the vertical asymptotes and one-sided behavior of <m>g(x)=\dfrac{3x+6}{x^2-9}</m>.</p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>
